{{Infobox military conflict | conflict = Rhamu Incident | partof = [[Ogaden War]] | image = | caption = | date = 29 June 1977 | place = [[Northern Frontier District]], [[Kenya]] | result = Somali army successfully crossed into the [[Sidamo Province|Sidamo]] Region of [[Ethiopia]] | combatant1 = {{flagicon|Kenya}} [[Military of Kenya|Kenyan military]], [[Kenyan Police]] | combatant2 = {{flagicon|Somalia}} [[Military of Somalia|Somali National Army]], [[WSLF]] | commander1 = | commander2 = | strength1 = Unknown | strength2 = 1500 | casualties1 = 30 soldiers and police officers killed. | casualties2 = Unknown }}
The '''Rhamu Incident''', on the 29 June 1977, was a brief armed conflict between [[Kenya]] and [[Somalia]], in which the latter invaded the [[Northern Frontier District]] on the eve of the [[Ogaden War]]. A force of 1500 [[Somali people|Somali]] soldiers attacked a [[border post]], and killed 30 [[Kenyan Police|Kenyan police officer]]s and [[Military of Kenya|soldiers]].<ref>Pg 86 - Husein Dualleh - From Barre to Aideed: Somalia : the agony of a nation</ref> The Somali army did not stay as the objective of their mission was to invade [[Ethiopia]] from a different side through [[Kenya]]. [[Rhamu]], situated on the Ethiopian-Kenyan border, lay on the road to the [[Sidamo Province|Sidamo]] region, and was considered a strategic point of entrance. The [[Federal Government of Somalia|Somali government]] denied the invasion, and claimed to have no knowledge of the incident.
